<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM AND OTHERS</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 28 10:51:39 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I am eighteen and live in South Africa. Even though I am far removed from having family that were affected by the war and having to deal with post-war stress,I still deal with the war and all the others that have come and gone in my lifetime. I agree with Joel,people need to talk about the war. Family's need to listen to the stories and to understand. It's all good and well having hundreds of movies made about it etc,etc but until the post-war generation and others still to come hear what the war generation have to say nothing is going to change and we'll carry on and on making movies about it that are all nice and compacted and we can walk away from. I have an uncle that was a prisoner of war in the Angolian war and until about a year ago I had never fully understood it and had somehow managed to idealise it ! But after speaking to him I hold him in respect,he did what he thought right and now regrets it but making him feel ashamed about it is doing no-one any good. To deal with it he needed to talk about it and not be placed in a corner and told to be quiet. The Vietam war and many others like it were horrific and yet still we have not dealt with them,or more the post-war syndrome. Talking is the key word here and I think that everybody needs to. Tell your family because maybe they need to know,to help you and to help themselves maybe understand why you did what you did etc. <br>
 
